04835nam a22006255i 9780822391807DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223918077 a10.1515/97808223918072doi  a(DE-B1597)553081  a(OCoLC)1202623271  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF2849.22.G85bC2817 2010 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a980.03/50922221 aDrinot, Paulo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChe's Travels :bThe Making of a Revolutionary in 1950s Latin America /cPaulo Drinot. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (315 p.) :b4 photos, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPoint of Departure -- tBeauty and Bounty in Che’s Chile -- tAwaiting the Blood of a Truly Emancipating Revolution -- t‘‘Putting Up’’ with Violence -- tChe Guevara and Venezuela -- tThe National Revolution and Bolivia in the 1950s -- t‘‘Not in All of America Can There Be Found a Country as Democratic as This One’’ -- tBetween Bohemianism and a Revolutionary Rebirth -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aErnesto “Che” Guevara twice traveled across Latin America in the early 1950s. Based on his accounts of those trips (published in English as The Motorcycle Diaries and Back on the Road), as well as other historical sources, Che’s Travels follows Guevara, country by country, from his native Argentina through Chile, Peru, Colombia, and Venezuela, and then from Argentina through Bolivia, Peru, Guatemala, and Mexico. Each essay is focused on a single country and written by an expert in its history. Taken together, the essays shed new light on Che’s formative years by analyzing the distinctive societies, histories, politics, and cultures he encountered on these two trips, the ways they affected him, and the ways he represented them in his travelogues. In addition to offering new insights into Guevara, the essays provide a fresh perspective on Latin America’s experience of the Cold War and the interplay of nationalism and anti-imperialism in the crucial but relatively understudied 1950s. Assessing Che’s legacies in the countries he visited during the two journeys, the contributors examine how he is remembered or memorialized; how he is invoked for political, cultural, and religious purposes; and how perceptions of him affect ideas about the revolutions and counterrevolutions fought in Latin America from the 1960s through the 1980s.ContributorsMalcolm DeasPaulo DrinotEduardo ElenaJudith EwellCindy ForsterPatience A. SchellEric ZolovAnn Zulawski  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aDeas, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrinot, Paulo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElena, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwell, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForster, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchell, Patience A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZolov, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZulawski, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107118370 cprintz978082234748440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391807?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391807423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/c